Finding optimal number of clusters

Here, we provide a simple solution. The idea is to compute k-means clustering using di erent values of clusters k. Next, the wss (within sum of square) is drawn according to the number of clusters. The location of a bend (knee) in the plot is generally considered as an indicator of the appropriate number of clusters.

fviz_nbclust(df, kmeans, method = "wss") +
geom_vline(xintercept = 4, linetype = 2)

fviz_nbclust(df, kmeans, method = "silhouette")

Compute k-mean clustering

As k-means clustering algorithm starts with k randomly selected centroids, itâ€™s always recommended to use the set.seed() function in order to set a seed for Râ€™s random number generator. The aim is to make reproducible the results, so that the reader of this article will obtain exactly the same results as those shown below.

set.seed(123)
km.res <- kmeans(df, 4, nstart = 25)

Visualizing

fviz_cluster(km.res, data = df, palette = c("#2E9FDF", "#00AFBB", "#E7B800", "#FC4E07"),
  ellipse.type = "euclid", # Concentration ellipse
  star.plot = TRUE, # Add segments from centroids to items
  repel = TRUE, # Avoid label overplotting (slow)
  ggtheme = theme_minimal()
  )

Using hierarchical K-Means Clustering

The algorithm is summarized as follow: 1. Compute hierarchical clustering and cut the tree into k-clusters 2. Compute the center (i.e the mean) of each cluster 3. Compute k-means by using the set of cluster centers (defined in step 2) as the initial cluster centers

res.hk <- hkmeans(df, 4)

Visualize the tree

fviz_dend(res.hk, cex = 0.6, palette = "jco",
          rect = TRUE, rect_border = "jco", rect_fill = TRUE)

Visualize the hkmeans final clusters

fviz_cluster(res.hk, palette = "jco", repel = TRUE,
             ggtheme = theme_classic())

Compare Results

rand.index(res.hk$cluster, km.res$cluster)
## [1] 1
